<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Deadlock Ahead for Cyprus Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The second round of direct talks
on the Cyprus issue collapsed last Friday, an omen of a fresh
deadlock in the divided island's peace process.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-led five-day talks were held in Glion-sur-Montreaux,
Switzerland, between Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides on the
Greek Cypriot side and the Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
with an aim to reach a comprehensive solution to the protracted
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The talks ended in failure as the Turkish Cypriot side insisted
on the suspension by the European Union (EU) of its planned
accession negotiations with Cyprus first.
</P>
<P>
Denktash charged the EU for throwing a "bombshell" into the
peace process by deciding to open access negotiations with Cyprus
next year, while Clerides blamed Denktash for the failure of the
talks.
</P>
<P>
Signs of bad luck for peace process had appeared even before
the start of the Glion negotiations. On July 15 the EU reaffirmed
its accession talks with Cyprus, a step it believes helpful to the
peaceful solution of the island's problem.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops invaded and took over the
northern third in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
But the EU move elicited strong reactions from Turkey and the
Turkish Cypriot side while Denktash threatened a boycott of the
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
In a move apparently designed to cow the EU, Denktash and
Turkish high-ranking officials announced on July 20 a series of
steps toward partial integration of the Turkish occupied northern
Cyprus with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is the only country which recognizes the "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus (TRNC)" declared by the Turkish
Cypriots unilaterally in 1983.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and the Turkish Cypriot side said the Greek Cypriot side
should not negotiate accession with the EU without participation
of the Turkish Cypriot side. They maintained that Cyprus cannot
become a member of the EU before a Cyprus settlement.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus applied for the EU full membership in 1990. The EU
decided in March 1995 that the accession talks with Cyprus would
start six months after the end of the EU Intergovernmental
Conference.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that some EU envoys on the wings of the Glion
direct talks exerted pressure on Denktash to make compromise on
Cyprus' EU accession course and accept a U.N. document on the
talks, but only to be rejected.
</P>
<P>
Still, the U.N. is expected to make fresh peace efforts to
break the deadlock, although there is little hope for a
breakthrough any time before the presidential election scheduled
for next February in government-controlled southern part of the
island, observers said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and international community have been trying for
decades to reunite this island nation as a bi-communal, bi-zonal
federation through peace talks, but so far no tangible results
have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
