<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EMU to Suffer Speculative Attacks: Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The European Monetary Union
(EMU), due to be launched on January 1 1999, will offer huge
opportunities for speculators to make millions by attacking the
single currency from the start, according to a leading economist.
</P>
<P>
Former head of Britain's National Economic Development Office
Walter Eltis was quoted by press reports as saying today that the
timetable for the EMU has been designed in such a way that it
offers speculators a free run.
</P>
<P>
Eltis focused on the period between the start of the final
stage of the EMU on January 1 1999 and conversion of national
currencies to the Euro in mid-2002.
</P>
<P>
The big danger is that traders will launch speculative attacks
on vulnerable currencies in an effort to force them out of the new
system, he said.
</P>
<P>
"As soon as the possibility of departure of one or more
countries from EMU between 1999 and 2002 is recognized, movement
towards the D-mark will not be confined to those who are exposed
to weaker currencies through trade or holdings of debt denominated
in their money."
</P>
<P>
"There will be staggering opportunities for profit at the
expense of those who, like the British government in 1992, seek to
hang on to exchange rates which they can not in the end sustain,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the European Union finance ministers and
central bankers have recognised this potential flaw in the final
run-up to the planned single currency, but they are powerless to
do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
However, Eltis noted that once national currencies have been
replaced by the single currency, the EMU system will be safer from
speculators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
