<HEADLINE> Iranian President Calls on Iraq to Release Iranian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami today called on Iraq to comply with its international
commitments and free the Iranian prisoners of war (POWs) still
held in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president made the call in a meeting with the
former POWs to mark their return in 1988, according to the
official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
The POWs is one of the major issues that block the improvement
of bilateral relations between the two former enemies who fought a
bitter war from 1980 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
Iran claimed that Iraq still holds more than 15,000 Iranian
POWs according to the documents it has. But Iraq repeatedly
rejected the claim.
</P>
<P>
Khatami expressed hope that Iraq will abide by its
international commitments and pay reparations for the losses that
its aggression (1980-1988 war) inflicted on Iran.
</P>
<P>
The 54-year-old president voiced deep concern about the fate
of the POWs still languishing in Iraqi prisons, saying "Iran will
do its utmost through international organizations to pressure Iraq
to release all Iranian POWs."
</P>
<P>
On the necessity of peace and security in the region, Khatami
said that "today, the need for consolidating peace in the region
is felt much more than any other time before and that the nations
themselves are able to secure peace in the region."
</P>
<P>
He also called the regional states to solve differences among
themselves peacefully and prepare grounds for development in all
economic, political and cultural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
