<HEADLINE> Six More Killed in Kenya's Port City Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Six more Kenyans were killed
last night and this morning in the port city of Mombasa, bringing
the death toll to 31 since Wednesday, the Kenya Television
Network (KTN) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Five people were killed and dozens of people injured during
the attacks by more than 100 gangsters at the Shauri Yako slum
area, eight kilometers north of Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
Another person was shot by police and his body burned by angry
villagers Sunday morning after local people in the area raided a
neighboring slum area, accusing the people there of attacking
them.
</P>
<P>
About 100 roadside kiosks and dozens of houses in the Maweni
and Kongowea areas of Mombasa were burned down today by
unidentified attackers.
</P>
<P>
According to the Coast Provincial police officer Francis
Gichuki, the incidents are not connected to the Wednesday night
raid when gangsters killed seven policemen and eight civilians at
Likoni Police Station and Likoni Ferry Tourist Police Unit in
Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
Since the Likoni attack, Kenyan army and navy had joined the
police in the massive manhunt for the gang of marauders and in
recovering weapons and ammunition stolen from the Likoni Police
Station.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan police spokesman Peter Kimanthi said that they had
killed seven of the gangsters, recovered two of the stolen guns
and made 40 arrests.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Lands and Settlement Noah Ngala today told the
Kenya News Agency that Coast Provincial Members of Parliament
would hold a meeting in Mombasa to discuss the continuous
violence during the past five days.
</P>
<P>
The motive of the recent violent attacks in Mombasa is not
clear yet, but local residents said that those killed had mainly
been people who originally came from up-country to the coastal
region.
</P>
<P>
Leaflets distributed in the port city say, "The time has come
for us original inhabitants of the coast to claim what is rightly
ours. We must remove these invaders from our land."  
</P>
</TEXT>
