<HEADLINE> Clean-Beach Campaign Launched in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Lebanese today went
out to the beach and joined in the one-day campaign to clean up
the Lebanese coastlines along the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
The campaign, the biggest clean-up since the end of the civil
war in 1990, was co-organized by the Operation Big Blue
Association (OBBA), the Environment Association and the
non-governmental organizations, with the support of the ministry
of environment, scout organizations and various municipalities.
</P>
<P>
"This is really a national effort. We are fighting for one
cause," said Hazem Idriss, head of OBBA, at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"Every year, Mediterranean countries clean up their beaches and
every year we are the ones seen as the polluters and are left
out," he said, adding that "this time we will show them otherwise."
</P>
<P>
Idriss, a scuba diving instructor, estimated that at least
25,000 people across the country have taken part in the operation.
</P>
<P>
Besides cleaning up a number of coastlines, he said, the more
important task of the campaign is to draw more attention of the
public to the issue of environment.
</P>
<P>
"The sea is in very bad shape. All industrial, chemical waste
is dumped and accumulates on the bottom of the sea which forms a
chemical mud residue," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rubbish collected today will be sold to Lebanese companies
for recycling in an effort to educate people about waste
reduction, separation and recycling, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
