<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 African States to Establish Economic Grouping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Presidents of five African
countries have agreed in principle to establish a regional
economic grouping among them.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of Libya, Burkina Fasso, Chad, Mali and Niger
reached the consensus during their two-day summit which concluded
in the Libyan capital city of Tripoli Saturday, reports reaching
here today said.
</P>
<P>
The idea was proposed by Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in line
with the directives of the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
that call for groupings and integration among member states,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested that Libya open up its Mediterranean shores
to the land-locked African states so that they might promote their
trade with European and Mediterranean states.
</P>
<P>
Quoting sources close to the summit, the reports added that the
heads of the five African states have agreed to conclude an
economic pact on the establishment of the grouping, and that it
would be signed in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Gaddafi also invited Tunisia, Algerian, Morocco, Mauritanian
and Egypt to join the proposed grouping. Invitation will also be
addressed to Nigeria to joint the grouping, because the Nigerian
president failed to attend the Tripoli summit for health reasons,
the reports said
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the sources said, the expected pact for the
proposed grouping will have "greater chances of success" as
compared to previous attempts in the field of cooperation among
the coastal Saharan African states. They attributed this to the
fact that "all precautions have been taken" this time.
</P>
<P>
The sources pointed out that Libya would dispatch delegations
to other countries of the region to brief their leaders about the
idea.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the leaders have decided to consolidate ties
among their states, and have charged their foreign ministers to
discuss the practical ways and means to put that into effect.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the concerned states will meet in
September to prepare for the second summit during which the pact
is likely to be endorsed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
