<DOCNO> XIE19970818.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President Signs Education Reform Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel today signed a controversy education reform bill into law,
marking the initial victory of the secularists.
</P>
<P>
Demirel wasted no time in signing the eight-year compulsory
education bill which was adopted by the Parliament by a margin of
35 votes Saturday, according to the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the president made the move to show
his firm support for the Mesut Yilmaz's government, which proposed
the education reform scheme, and other secularists.
</P>
<P>
So far, Demirel has stopped short of making any comment on the
bill.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a rally in Hacibektas, a town in central Anatolian
province this morning, Prime Minister Yilmaz said that the new law
concerning the education system was a gift to the people who back
the country's secularism.
</P>
<P>
The education reform bill, which touched off the strong
opposition from the pro-Islamic Welfare Party (RP) and its
followers, was one of the republic' most important bills, Yilmaz
added.
</P>
<P>
This controversial bill was passed in the Parliament by 277 to
242 following a white hot debate, earlier reports said.
</P>
<P>
According to the new law, a large number of religious schools
have to be closed, which is widely seen as a heavy blow to the
conservative Islamists.
</P>
<P>
Students, if they like, have to finish their eight years of
compulsory education before they enter religious schools to
study the Koran.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of the education reform bill enraged RP leader and
former prime minister Necmettin Erbakan, who has tried hard to
block the passage of the Education Ministry-initiated program.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan, who was forced by the military to step down due to his
pro-fundamentalist policies on June 18, said that his party would
set up a special commission which is to appeal to the
Constitutional Court for the annulment of the new law.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a group of Islamic businessmen in Istanbul, the
largest city of Turkey, on Friday, Tansu Ciller, chairwoman of
the opposition True Path Party, also criticized the eight-year
compulsory education plan, describing is as "outdate."
</P>
<P>
Ciller, who served as deputy prime minister in the former
Erbakan government, said that the education reform bill was a
"big trick," adding it would push the country to the edge of
darkness.
</P>
<P>
The Yilmaz government, however, stated that this education
reform bill was extremely important for the continuation of
Turkey's democracy and secularist system, saying it would prevent
fundamentalists from expanding in the secular republic.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military has voiced its support to Yilmaz and his
government's efforts for the adoption of the significant
bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
