<DOCNO> XIE19970818.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afro-Asian Organization Urges Revival of Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The Afro-Asian People's Solidarity
Organization (AAPSO) today appealed to the world community for
saving the Middle East peace process from dangers surrounding it.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo-based AAPSO asked in a statement the United Nations
to send a fact-finding committee to investigate the July 30 blasts
in West Jerusalem and determine those responsible and to explore
policies which would provide a proper climate for peace.
</P>
<P>
Two suicide bombs killed 16 people in a crowded Jerusalem
market just as the two sides prepared to resume peace talks that
have been frozen since March over Israel's construction of a
Jewish housing project in East Jerusalem, a place claimed by the
Palestinians as their future capital.
</P>
<P>
The organization said the recent shuttle tour in the region of
U.S. Mideast Peace Coordinator Dennis Ross did not achieve "any
negligible progress."
</P>
<P>
"Ross came to the area following the blasts in Jerusalem,
ignoring the base of the peace process which had stopped before
the suicide bombings because of Israel's insistence on building
more settlements," it said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Israel was demolishing the homes of
Palestinians in accordance with a plan which is aimed at Judaizing
Palestinian lands on the pretext that they were not licensed.
</P>
<P>
The United States shoulders a big responsibility to save the
peace process, it stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Washington's silence and bias to Israel will contribute to an
explosion of the situation in the Middle East and all chances of
peace will be lost," AAPSO warned in its statement.
</P>
<P>
Ross' intense four-day shuttle diplomacy early this month has
achieved nothing more than helping restore the Palestinian-Israeli
mechanism of security coordination.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has announced she
would make her first trip to the region in the coming few weeks to
push across a major U.S. peace initiative that will focus on
accelerated talks on a final peace settlement and implementation
of the existing Israeli-Palestinian agreements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
