<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-17 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afro-Asian Organization Calls for US Role in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The Afro-Asian Peoples' Solidarity
Organization (AAPSO) today called on the United States and the
United Nations to help salvage the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"In light of the principles of the international law and
agreements signed between Israel and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA), the U.S. should step in to save the peace process
from dying," AAPSO said in a message sent to U.S. President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
It also called for lifting the sanctions imposed on the
Palestinian people after the July 30 suicide bombing attacks in
Jerusalem which killed 16 people, condemning the Israeli measures
as "unjust and irresponsible."
</P>
<P>
The Cairo-based organization today sent a message to PNA
President Yasser Arafat, voicing support for the Palestinians and
denouncing the Israeli policy.
</P>
<P>
In a third message sent in this respect to UN Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, AAPSO asked him to interfere immediatedly to alleviate
the suffering sustained by Palestinians due to the Israeli
policies.
</P>
<P>
AAPSO asked the UN to send a fact-finding committee to
investigate the July 30 blasts in West Jerusalem, determine those
responsible and explore policies which would provide a proper
climate for peace.
</P>
<P>
The bomb attacks took place in a crowded Jerusalem market just
as the PNA and Israel prepared to resume peace talks stopped over
Israel's construction in March of a housing project for Jews in
East Jerusalem. 
</P>
