<HEADLINE> Syria Says Ready to Talk With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The Syrian Minister of State
for Foreign Affairs Nasser Qaddour reiterated today that Syria is
prepared to resume negotiations with Israel from the very point
they were suspended.
</P>
<P>
Addressing participants in the political leadership training
seminars of the Feminist Union and the Revolution Youths Union
today, he said that Syria is struggling for the achievement of
just and comprehensive based on international legitimacy
resolutions and the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian minister pointed out that Israel has failed to abide
by the U.N. resolutions stipulating Israeli withdrawal from the
occupied Arab territories.
</P>
<P>
Qaddour emphasized that no one should ever think of the
prevalence of peace without Israeli withdrawal to the June 4, 1967
border lines, and the safeguarding of the established rights of
the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
He praised the positive EU role in the regional peace process,
pointing out that Syria has always welcomed EU participation in
the peace process from the very outset.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Syrian peace negotiations have been frozen since March
last year following a wave of suicide bombing attacks launched by
Islamic extremists against Israel, and tension between the two
countries has been brewing after the hardline Likud government
came to power in Israel in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Israel has repeatedly called for unconditional resumption of
the peace talks, while Syria insists that the negotiations should
restart from the point where they broke off: Israel's promise to
total withdrawal from the occupied Golan heights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
