<HEADLINE> Negotiations Between Sudanese Government, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The planned negotiations
between the Sudanese government and the John Garang opposition
movement scheduled Tuesday at the Kenyan capital of Nairobi have
been postponed.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese Foreign Minister Ali Mohamed Taha said he was informed
of the postponement by a cable from the Kenyan foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
Local radio today quoted Taha as saying the Kenyan government
has not revealed the cause of the postponement.
</P>
<P>
Taha said there might be several factors behind the
postponement, including the fact that Garang's Sudan People's
Liberation Army (SPLA) was not prepared for the negotiations as
announced earlier.
</P>
<P>
The minister criticized some states such as Uganda for carrying
out measures that would harm peace in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government had announced earlier this month that
the second round of negotiations with Garang would take place by
the end of August, under the umbrella of the Inter-Governmental
Authority on Drought and Development (IGADD), which embraces
Sudan, Kenya, Uganda, Ethiopia, Eritrea, Somalia and Djibouti as
members.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government had then expressed readiness to
negotiate with Garang at any place to be fixed by Kenyan President
Daniel Arap Moi, chairman of the current IGADD session.
</P>
<P>
The first round of negotiations brokered within the framework
of IGADD took place last May.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA has been fighting since 1983 for more independence for
the South's animists and Christians from the Islamic North. It
refused to join four other smaller rebel groups in signing a peace
agreement with the government in this April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
