<HEADLINE> Netanyahu's Adviser Meets Arafat, Praising PNA's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Yitzhak Molcho, Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's attorney, met secretly with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat overnight to commend Palestinian
cooperation in apprehending the murderers of an Israeli taxi
driver, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Molcho and Arafat was held in Gaza
Saturday night following the Palestinian court in Jericho
sentenced three Palestinians earlier in the day for murdering
Israeli cab driver Shmuel Ben Baruch Friday.
</P>
<P>
The court sentenced two of them to life sentence, and the
third 15 years in prison for killing Baruch in order to steal his
car. Molcho reportedly praised the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) for its quick actions in apprehending the murderers.
</P>
<P>
Molcho and Arafat also discussed other political issues,
including further bilateral security cooperation and results of
the just-concluded visit by United States peace envoy Dennis Ross
last week.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return to Washington Wednesday, Ross described the
restoration of Israeli-Palestinian security cooperation as one of
the major achievements of his four-day shuttle mission.
</P>
<P>
Despite the compliments on the PNA for its actions in smashing
the murder case, Molcho still demanded Arafat take more steps to
fight Islamic militant groups, such as Islamic Resistance Movement
(Hamas) and Islamic Jihad, as well as their infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Israeli, Palestinians and
U.S. security officials are scheduled to hold a new round of
talks Sunday night in the West Bank's Palestinian city Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
Jibril Rajoub and Mohammed Dahlan, the heads of Palestinian
Preventive Forces in West Bank and Gaza Strip, will discuss
further security cooperation with Ami Ayalon, chief of Israel's
General Security Service, and officials from the U.S. Central
Intelligence Agency station based in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
This meeting is another positive sign for further thawing of
the chilly Israeli-Palestinian relations since the twin suicide
bombings in Jerusalem on July 30, which killed 16 people and
forced the cancellation of the originally set resumption of peace
talks. Hamas has claimed responsibility for the attack.
</P>
<P>
Israel is demanding for PNA's specific steps to launch a
long-term crackdown on terrorist organizations and their
infrastructure as a precondition for resuming the peace
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
