<HEADLINE> Yeltsin-Maskhadov Meet in Kremlin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and Chechen leader Aslan Maskhadov have agreed to set up a
Russian-Chechen joint commission to draft a document concerning
the freedom of Chechnya, Russian media reported today.
</P>
<P>
"If the Commission fails to arrive at a consensus, Maskhadov
and I will meet at the negotiating table and settle all the
issues," said Yeltsin, who held a 90-minute talk with Maskhadov in
the Kremlin today.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Maskhadov suggested that Russia and
Chechnya sign a treaty recognizing Chechnya as an independent
country.
</P>
<P>
Maskhadov gave the draft treaty on Chechen independence to
Yeltsin today and said he hoped the treaty would be signed
following talks between the two presidents.
</P>
<P>
Maskhadov said he also hoped the dispute between Moscow and
Grozny could be settled through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
"One can't engage in hairsplitting in dealings between Chechnya
and Russia, as this may lead to new bloodshed. We must stop
fighting and start tackling our problems in a diplomatic way," the
Chechen president said.
</P>
<P>
A peace deal signed a year ago ended the 20-month war between
Russia and Chechnya. Under the deal, Russia agreed to delay a
decision on Chechnya's future political status until 2001.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two leaders discussed Chechnya's demand
for 260 billion U.S. dollars of war compensation from Russia and
the issue of hostages detained in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
The number of people missing in Chechnya, including war
prisoners, totals more than 1,400. 
</P>
</TEXT>
