<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Transportation Tends to Ease Economic Bottlenecks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- China has basically formed a
nationwide comprehensive transportation network to ease the
bottleneck the formerly-lagging sector created in the national
economy in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Since the 14th National Congress of the Communist Party of
China was held in 1992, total passenger transport volume has
increased by an annual average of 9.1 percent to end at 12.45
billion people in 1996, while passenger turnover reached 914.2
billion person/km, an average rise of 8.2 percent, according to a
report recently released by the State Statistics Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
Cargo volume amounted to 12.96 billion tons, an average growth
of 5.6 percent, while cargo turnover enjoyed an average rise of
5.4 percent to stand at 3.64 trillion ton/km.
</P>
<P>
The cargo handling capacity at major coastal ports had been
increased from 530 million tons to 850 million by the end of last
year, rising by an average 9.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Priority was given to railway and highway construction to
improve transportation structure.
</P>
<P>
During the period, 148.4 billion yuan was spent on railway
construction to expand the total mileage to 117,618 km, with an
average increase of 2.3 percent. Nearly a third of them had
double-track rails and 17.4 percent were electric.
</P>
<P>
The improved railway technology and equipment made it possible
for China to raise the speed limits nationwide on April 1, the
report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970818.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Transportation Tends to Ease Economic Bottlenecks (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some 145,000 km of highways were added in the past five years,
increasing by an average 2.6 percent. At the end of 1996, China
had 3,422 km of expressways, nearly six-fold that of 1991. And
roads ran to all counties, 98 percent of townships and 80 percent
of villages in the country.
</P>
<P>
And in water routes construction, special attention was placed
on key projects and loading capacity improvements of containers
for major cargo. As a result, China now boasts world-standard
freighters to convey containers.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there were 406 10,000-ton deepwater berths at major
coastal ports at the end of 1996, and 1,703 docks and berths at
inland waters.
</P>
<P>
Aviation infrastructure has taken giant leaps during the
five-year period, with 21 new airports added and another 21
extended, bringing the total number of airports to 142 by the end
of last year. China had 449 airplanes for air transportation and
876 air routes, with 1.63 million km of mileage in operation in
136 cities. It has also opened air service to 58 cities abroad.
</P>
<P>
The transport and communications sector began to raise money to
ease capital shortage pressure. By the first half of this year,
the sector had five enterprises listed on overseas stock markets,
to raise some 11 billion yuan of funds.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC) has formed
three enterprise groups and begun share-holding system experiments
with other companies. And by the end of last year, CAAC had hired
241 airplanes and used 11.8 billion US dollars of overseas
investment.
</P>
<P>
Hainan Airlines took in overseas investment to become the first
Sino-foreign joint venture in the sector.
</P>
<P>
China has also made marked progress in pipeline transportation,
the SSB report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970818.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Textiles Exports Register Strong Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 18 (Xinhua) -- India's exports of textiles,
including handicrafts, touched 418.2 billion rupees (about 11.95
billion u.s. dollars) at the end of fiscal year 1996-97
(April-March), showing a 17.7 percent growth over the previous
year, Press Trust of India reported today.
</P>
<P>
Announcing this at a meeting here today, Textiles Minister of
Textile R.L. Jalappa said that textiles, which constituted one
third of the country's total exports, was the largest net foreign
exchange earner for India.
</P>
<P>
He said the Indian garment industry could achieve further
heights, if it paid closer attention to international quality
standards and eco-friendly aspects.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Indian garment exporters would face stiff
competition, both in quality and price, the minister urged
exporters to upgrade their technology and produce quality products
which were capable of meeting international standards.  
</P>
