<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Geo-Information Science Conference Opens in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Beijing today welcomed more than
200 scientists to a five-day Geo-information conference slated to
cover methods of accurately forecasting adverse weather conditions
and monitoring the environment.
</P>
<P>
The Fourth International Workshop on Geographical Information
Systems has drawn participants from some 20 countries, including
Australia, Canada, Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
One of the major topics of the meeting will be how to apply
remote sensing technology, which has been used not only to assess
output of farm produce on large acreages, but also to control
subsoil drainage and urban traffic flow.
</P>
<P>
China has developed the technology in the past decade. Its
existing comprehensive monitoring system can observe floods,
drought or other natural disasters, and appraise losses within one
or two days.
</P>
<P>
Geo-information combines comprehensive geological information
networks, global positioning systems, advanced telecommunications,
and an accurate data collection and sharing system.
</P>
<P>
The participants also will confer on how best to use technology
for global and regional resources surveying and environmental
protection. A number of lectures will be held and several papers
presented.
</P>
<P>
Organizers of the meeting are the Chinese Academy of Sciences
(CAS), the State Geological Remote Sensing Center and the
International Eurasian Academy of Sciences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
