<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, US Sign Oil, Gas Development Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- China National Petroleum
Corporation (CNPC) and Enron Oil &AMP; Gas (China) Ltd. signed here
today a contract on the joint development of oil and natural gas
resources in southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
According to the contract, Enron as the sole operator is fully
responsible for the drilling in the pilot test period and
shoulders all investment risks. The contract is the widely-used
product-sharing agreement.
</P>
<P>
Located north of Suining and Nanchong prefectures in Sichuan,
the resources block occupies an area of 7,525 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
CNPC started the oil and gas exploration in the Chuanzhong
block in the 1950s. Due to the complicated geographical
conditions, the exact area of oil-bearing layer and actual oil and
gas reserve still have not been confirmed.
</P>
<P>
In term of technical difficulty, work to be done in the block
is the most complicated ever done by a foreign company in China.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Yongkang, president of CNPC, said, "Any breakthrough made
by this Sino-US cooperative project would surely have a positive
impact on the further development of oil and gas resources in the
central part of the province." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970818.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business Halts as Students Plan March In S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Business in Sierra Leone's
capital here is completely shut down today, as heavily armed
police, wearing gas masks and carrying batons, are patroling the
major streets to prevent a planned march called by students.
</P>
<P>
The "Democracy March" called for by the National Union of
Sierra Leone Students (NUSS), was said to aim to press the
military government of Major Johnny Paul Koroma which seized
power on May 25, to return rule "immediately back to the (ousted)
civilian government".
</P>
<P>
Another "one man march" by human rights activist lawyer
Sulaiman Banja Tejan Sie was also banned by police.
</P>
<P>
The streets of the capital Freetown remain clear except
security vehicles, with traders at the central market reduced to
a minimum.
</P>
<P>
Inspector General of Police Teddy Williams in a statement
broadcast over state radio, banned the march "in consideration of
the general security situation" in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"All security forces are on alert throughout the country to
ensure that absolute law and order is maintained," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The president of NUSS, Ibrahim Jalloh speaking to Xinhua from
a hideout in the capital said in a defiant mood, "we shall
demonstrate whether the authorities like it or not. We don't want
an illegal government and they should hand back power to the
civilian government."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in a press release issued today, the Ministry of
Education accused students residing in campuses in two colleges
in the capital, of "hatching the mobilization plans" for today's
march.
</P>
<P>
Schools and colleges have been closed unofficially since the
coup by education officials who said they will reopen in October.
</P>
<P>
Today's statement asked "those students still remaining in
campuses to leave immediately or face the consequences."
</P>
<P>
About 100 foreign students, mainly from west and eastern
Africa as well as from the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
will be affected.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the task force commander of the West African Peace
Keeping Force (ECOMOG), colonel Max Khobe, has denied the
involvement of Nigeria in today's march.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview, Khobe said, "we are not involved. We
are here on a specific mandate to help restore civilian rule to
the country."
</P>
<P>
"If it is determined that the activities of the illegal
military Government pose a grave threat to the lives of innocent
civilians, then ECOMOG may be forced to take swift and decisive
action to eliminate the threat," he added.
</P>
<P>
Asked when Nigerians troops, now occupying the country's
airport, would leave, he said, "We will not move until (ousted
president) Tejan Kabbah is restored to power."
</P>
<P>
The outburst of heavy gunfire caused commotion in the city
itself, sending people rushing for shelter and local markets to
close.
</P>
<P>
Gunners from the Sierra Leone navy fired back toward the
airport from their depot in the city center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
