<HEADLINE> Italian-Run Hospital in Somalia Attacked, 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Three Somali guards at the
Italian-run hospital in Jalalaqsi district have been killed
following an attack by unidentified gunmen.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the local radios in Jalalaqsi district of Hiran
region, about 200 kilometers North of Mogadishu, said the attack
came last week when three Italian doctors are operating in the
hospital, but none was hurt.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports all three expatriates working for the
Italian aid agency, Committato Europeo Fundo Agricolo (CEFA), in
the hospital were evacuated temporarily to the neighboring town
of Jowhar.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the attack against the hospital remains
obscure. However, sources say disputes over the administration of
the hospital by local Somalis have prompted the attack.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, local elders from the region are reported to be
working on ways to ease the tension and prevent further attacks
against the hospital.
</P>
<P>
The elders are also planning for the possibilities of
redeploying the evacuated doctors who are still in Jowhar town
for security precautionary measures.
</P>
<P>
In another development, some unidentified Somali gunmen have
opened fire on a civilian vehicle working for a local
humanitarian agency known as ADRA-SAACID in Burane village, 23 km
North of Jowhar town Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to eyewitness, two of the bodyguards of the vehicle
were killed and the driver was wounded as the result of the
shooting carried out by gunmen manning a checkpoint outside the
village.
</P>
<P>
It is not yet known the motive behind the attack. But local
authorities in Jowhar district, 90 km north of Mogadishu,
described the incident as an isolated incident which is part of
the banditry attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
