<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Nusrat's Death, National Loss to Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani textile city of
Faisalabad, about 200 km south of here, was plunged into mourning
as the country's music maestro Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan was laid to
rest there Sunday afternoon at his ancestral graveyard.
</P>
<P>
Nusrat, who fused western rhythms into a mystic, classical
style of chorus singing called "Qawali" in the subcontinent, died
Saturday at 49 of a heart attack arising from Kidney problems in
London.
</P>
<P>
The legendary musician and singer, who was on his way to the
United States for kidney transplant operation, died on the same
date on which the king of Rock and Roll, Elvis Presley, had died
exactly 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of wailing people including a large number of fans,
musicians and relatives late Sunday attended the funeral
procession of the legendary singer in Faisalabad and everybody
wanted to give shoulder to the coffin mounted on bamboos,
according to reports monitored here.
</P>
<P>
Many people fainted with grief when having the last sight of
their favorite singer, whose music touched the heart and soul of
the listeners and built a direct rapport with them.
</P>
<P>
Shops in the main markets were closed and the few tea stalls
opened repeatedly played one of Nusrat's hit songs "May No One
Suffer the Agony of Missing a Beloved".
</P>
<P>
Earlier Sunday, funeral prayers attended by senior government
officials were offered at the Data Darbar shrine in Lahore, about
250 km southeast of here, after Nusrat's body was flown in the
capital of the eastern Punjab province from London amid emotional
scenes.
</P>
<P>
Born in Faisalabad in 1948, Nusrat was expected by his father,
a renowned exponent of Qawali, to be a doctor. However, the eldest
son of the family learnt to play the harmonium secretly. The
talented boy joined his family's Qawali party soon after the death
of his father in 1964 and became leader of the group.
</P>
<P>
After being spotted by a radio producer at a festival on March
23, 1965, Nusrat, who had the distinction of popularizing a new
blend of music through a mix of Qawali and technology, began to
enthrall the Pakistani music lovers and later those in India, the
United Kingdom, the United States and several other countries.
</P>
<P>
In Pakistan, his popularity might be gauged by the fact that
Pakistan television regularly invited him to record patriotic
songs to be telecast on the occasions of national importance. His
style of singing always brought emotional climaxes to the
listeners and was regarded as a supreme expression of religious
devotion and worship.
</P>
<P>
Nusrat's international profile took a significant leap in the
late 1980s when he approached by producer Peter Gabriel to sing on
the sound track of Hollywood's film "The Last Temptation of
Christ".
</P>
<P>
The untimely death of Nusrat, was felt deeply in Pakistan.
President Farooq Leghari and Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif paid
eloquent tributes, terming his death a "national loss".
</P>
<P>
The All Musicians' Association has declared a three-day
mourning period and announced there would be no recording of any
music programs during that time in memory of Nusrat.
</P>
<P>
"To me his death is a personal loss," said a music researcher
here. "I believe people like him are not meant to live long. They
are like meteors, who burn out very quickly."
</P>
<P>
"In the death of Nusrat, the country has lost one of the
greatest singers, musicians," Culture Minister Sheikh Rashid Ahmad
said when expressing his deep grief. "Nusrat has bridged the gap
between Oriental and Western music with his deep understanding of
the art."
</P>
<P>
Another important factor that makes Nusrat's death such a big
tragedy for Pakistanis lies in that he was also a philanthropist.
It is reported that Nusrat had been financially helping some 150
poor families in his home city Faisalabad.
</P>
<P>
"His death had left us orphaned," said the wailing women and
children, to whom Nusrat had been secretly giving monthly
stipends, at Sunday's burial ceremony.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
