<HEADLINE> China's Housing Policy Successful: Habitat Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Chief of U.N. Center for
Human Settlement (Habitat) today spoke highly of China's housing
policy, saying it has successfully established "a very good
example for the rest of the world".
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has made continuous efforts to build
high-quality houses for people with low incomes, scoring
"tremendous achievements" by constructing nine billion square
meters of floor areas in buildings in the past 10 years, Habitat
Executive Director Wally N'dow told Xinhua here.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure construction expands very fast in China's big
and medium-sized cities, he said in an interview, citing the
improvement of living conditions in Shanghai and the high-tech
sewerage system in the southern Chinese city of Fushan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he praised China's strategy on township
construction since it has been easing pressures on big cities to
a large extent.
</P>
<P>
The construction of medium- and small-sized towns in China
will make rapid progress and set an example in the human
settlements development in the whole world, he predicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
