<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Current Account Deficit Soars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' current account
soared to 2.02 billion U.S. dollars during the first four months
this year, a 38-percent increase over the same period last year,
the Philippine Central Bank said today.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said a rise in trade deficit and a drop in
services account surplus contributed to the jump in the current
account deficit.
</P>
<P>
During the period under review, the country's trade deficit
expanded 7 percent to 3.71 billion dollars while the surplus in
services account dropped 37.4 percent to 1.45 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Current account summarizes a country's earnings from exports of
goods and services, minors cost of imports. The Philippines'
current account also includes remittances sent home by its
millions of overseas workers.
</P>
<P>
A deficit in current account may lead to a drop in
international reserves, a rise in foreign debt and other economic
problems.  
</P>
</TEXT>
