<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Coastal Areas Create New Jobs for Laid-Off Workers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Coastal areas in east China have
been successful in redistributing labor resources and creating new
jobs for laid-off workers, the People's Daily, China's leading
newspaper, reported today.
</P>
<P>
A front page article noted that in the reforms of state-owned
enterprises, re-employment of laid-off workers is a difficult
problem that needs to be handled carefully.
</P>
<P>
Profound changes are taking place in the relationship between
the state, the enterprises and the workers as China turns from a
planned economy to a market economy, the article noted.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990s, the article said, a total of 1.09 million people
in Shanghai, China's largest city, lost their original jobs, but
890,000 of them were offered a new job thanks to the city's
re-employment project.
</P>
<P>
"The scale of labor redistribution in Shanghai over recent
years is larger than the population of a medium-sized city," it
said.
</P>
<P>
It added that in Qingdao and Ningbo, coastal cities in east
China's Shandong and Zhejiang provinces, and in Hangzhou, capital
of Zhejiang Province, more than 10,000 surplus workers from these
cities' traditional textile and silk sectors have entered the
labor market with the help of local "re-employment service
centers."
</P>
<P>
Governments in the coastal areas have realized that shifting
from the traditional industries to various kinds of new markets,
setting up labor service enterprises and developing the service
sector are effective ways to create new job opportunities for the
surplus or laid-off workers, the article acknowledged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
