<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Coastal Areas Create New Jobs for Laid-Off Workers (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It said that laid-off workers are mostly from the traditional
industries, and their cultural and technical qualities usually
fall far short of the demands of newly-emerged industries,
industries applying high and new technologies and high-grade
service sectors such as information and finance.
</P>
<P>
Many laid-off people prefer to receive meager relief funds than
be engaged in some service jobs which are either risky or hard,
dirty and tiring, it said.
</P>
<P>
The article also noted that most laid-off workers in China
today are aged between 40 and 50, and that many of them graduated
from middle schools during the period of the Cultural Revolution
(1966-1976).
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that among the 43,386 laid-off workers in
Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong Province, nearly 46
percent are aged between 40 and 50, and women account for some 57
percent.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, the article said, the social security
system in the eastern areas is still far from being satisfactory,
and most provinces and cities in these areas are not yet able to
put all their laborers under the protection of social insurance.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, it said, governments in most areas in
east China have set up the minimum life guarantee system for the
laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
"In Shenzhen, the collection and distribution of the funds for
pension, medicare and industrial injury insurance are handled by
some special government institutions, and the city government has
set up a special committee to monitor the management of the fund,"
it noted.
</P>
<P>
It described social security guarantee as an "indispensable
cushion" and a "propeller" for the re-employment of laid-off
people.
</P>
<P>
"Only after a unified social security system that covers the
entire society has been built could we see the emergence of a
real, competitive and vigorous labor market," the article
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
