<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Coastal Areas Create New Jobs for Laid-Off Workers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since 1993, it said, the city government of Jinan, capital of
east China's Shandong Province, has provided support for over 40
enterprises from some 15 different sectors to set up 43 special
markets for the wholesale of various industrial products.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of the employees in these markets are
laid-off workers, it added.
</P>
<P>
Also in Jinan, a neighborhood committee has assisted unemployed
people in the neighborhood with running small private businesses,
such as restaurants, laundries, barber and tailoring shops, and
roadside vending.
</P>
<P>
The article said that it has become a common practice in
provinces and municipalities in east China to solve the problem of
laid-off workers through fostering the local labor markets.
</P>
<P>
There are now over 400 job placement offices in Shanghai, while
a computerized information network has been established in all
employment offices run by the local labor administration, the
article said.
</P>
<P>
In Ningbo, a female laid-off worker opened a private employment
office named "Lucky Strike," which specialized in helping laid-off
workers find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
The labor market in Shenzhen, a booming special economic zone
in south China's Guangdong Province, has attached first priority
to the employment of people with major troubles, such as couples
in which both spouses are jobless, single parents and elderly
women.
</P>
<P>
"In the vast eastern areas, a network of open and competitive
labor markets and an effective mechanism of market management have
been gradually taking shape," said the article.
</P>
<P>
However, it conceded that there remains a clearly noticeable
conflict between supply and demand in east China's labor markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
