<HEADLINE> KEDO Mission Departs for DPRK to Attend Reactor Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 18 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of the Korean
Peninsula Energy Development Organization (KEDO) left here today
for a ground-breaking ceremony for the construction of nuclear
reactors in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Traveling on a 3,800-ton-class training ship, the 81-member
mission will arrive at Yanghwa Port at 10:30 (local time) Tuesday,
a Yonhap News Agency report said today.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony to launch the construction of the two light-water
reactors in Shinpo of the DPRK's South Hamkyong Province will be
held at 14:00 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony will signal the full-scale launch of the reactor
construction project almost three years after the U.S. and the
DPRK signed the Geneva Agreement in October, 1994.
</P>
<P>
The delegation consists of 20 government representatives from
Seoul, Washington and Tokyo, eight officials from the KEDO
secretariat, eight from the KEDO's general member nations such as
Australia and Chile, 18 from corporate contractors and 27
reporters from three KEDO executive nations, South Korea, the
U.S. and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will return to South Korea Wednesday morning
after spending one night on the ship.  
</P>
