<HEADLINE> First Mail from DPRK Arrives in Seoul since Korean War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Letters from the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) arrived in Seoul last Saturday
for the first time since the outbreak of the Korean War in June,
1950.
</P>
<P>
The mail delivery included two letters from Park Young-chul,
head of the South Korean Electric Power Corporation's (KEPCO)
light-water reactor construction office in DPRK, and were
addressed to KEPCO President Lee Jong-hoon, KEPCO said today.
</P>
<P>
The envelopes carried the postmark of "Kumho, DPR of Korea,
July 4, 1997," and the sender's address of Kumho Atomic Power
Plant Construction Office, Foreigners' Quarters, Kumho District,
South Hamkyong Province, KEDO.
</P>
<P>
In one letter, Park inquired about President Lee's health while
in the other, he told his boss that the North (DPRK) had launched
international mail services from the reactor construction site,
according to Yonhap News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The telecommunication protocol signed in July last year between
the Korean Peninsula Energy Development Organization (KEDO) and
the DPRK paved the way for postal services between the two Koreas.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK has recently established an international post office
with a staff of 15 at the reactor construction site to handle the
new mail service between the DPRK and South Korea. The mail is
delivered to Seoul via Pyongyang and Beijing, Yonhap said.
</P>
</TEXT>
