<HEADLINE> Anjouan Island Governor on Comoros Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Governor Colonel Cheikh Allaoui
on the Indian Ocean island of Anjouan announced he was resigning
on Sunday, according to a report quoting witnesses as saying from
Moroni today.
</P>
<P>
Allaoui was appointed governor last month by Mohammed Taki,
president of the Islamic republic of the Comoros, during
pro-secession demonstrations on Anjouan.
</P>
<P>
"I offer you my sincerest apologies and i submit to you my
resignation," Allaoui told a rally in his home town of Domoni, 30
km southeast of Anjouan's capital Mutsamudu on Sunday, said the
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
He had backed Anjouan independence but defected to the
government in July after a meeting with Taki.
</P>
<P>
People at the rally responded with thunderous applause.
</P>
<P>
Under the Comoran constitution the governor is the highest
political authority on the island.
</P>
<P>
On Moheli island, which like Anjouan declared independence
from the Comoros Federation in August, pro-secessionists have
given governor Hachim Mohammed until today to submit his
resignation.
</P>
<P>
The secessionist-appointed Premier of Moheli, Soidri Ahmed,
said if he refused to resign he would be forced out.
</P>
<P>
Islanders on Anjouan and Moheli say they want to return to
French rule or become independent because they have received
little from the government except poverty and numerous coups
since independence from France in 1975.
</P>
<P>
The poverty in the Comoros, with a population of some 670,000,
paled in comparison with the prosperity on the island of Mayotte,
which voted against independence in 1975 and has remained under
French rule since.
</P>
<P>
However, France has denounced the secessionist unrest, saying
it could destabilize the whole region of Indian Ocean islands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
