<HEADLINE> Toyota To Invest 740 Million US dollars In Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Leading Japanese car maker
Toyota unveiled a plan today to spend up to 740 million U.S.
dollars in Australia through 2005 and set up a research and
development plant in Australia.
</P>
<P>
Toyota Australia President Osamu Komori said part of the
company's spending would be a 74 million U.S. dollars upgrade of
Altona plant in south-west of Melbourne to accommodate production
of a new six-cylinder car from the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Toyota said the new car would be a V6 vehicle modeled on the
company's Avalon vehicle in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The upgrade will increase the plant's capacity to possibly
140,000 cars per year compared to 80,000 vehicles at the moment.
</P>
<P>
Toyota also predicted that by 2000 its exports from Australia
would be twice the 244 million U.S. dollar worth of vehicles the
car-maker currently shipped.
</P>
<P>
The investment plan was hailed by Australian Prime Minister
John Howard as "extremely good news for investment and jobs in
Australia."
</P>
<P>
Under pressure from car producers in Australia, including
Toyota, the prime minister made a decision two months ago to
freeze tariffs on imported cars at 15 percent until 2005,
rejecting proposals for further tariff cuts before 2005.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the government was told privately
prior to the decision on tariffs that the higher rate of
protection would "influence" future investment decisions by Toyota
and the other multinational car manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Speaking today at a joint press conference with Toyota
officials, the prime minister described Toyota's decision as "a
vindication of a decision by my government two months ago for the
long-term future of the motor industry in Australia". 
</P>
</TEXT>
