<HEADLINE> Israel Decides to Partially Release Frozen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 18 (Xinhua) -- In a major step toward
breaking the ice in the Israeli-Palestinian ties, Israel decided
today to release 30 percent of tax revenues frozen following the
recent terror bombings in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu announced the move
following consultations with Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
and Foreign Minister David Levy.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the July 30's twin suicide bombings in
Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda market which killed 16 people and
wounded 170 others, Israel immediately retaliated by imposing
sanctions on the Palestinians, including a total closure and
freezing the transfer of 14 million dollars in tax revenues it
collected from Palestinians on the behalf of the Palestinian
National Authority.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's spokesman Shai Bazak said that Israel's step to
release part of the tax money was "a return for some steps" taken
by the PNA for its cooperation in investigating the Mahane Yehuda
Bombing and Palestinian police's quick action in apprehending
three Palestinians who killed an Israeli taxi driver last week.
</P>
<P>
He added that Israel still demanded the PNA take tougher
actions to crack down on militant organizations and their
infrastructure, promising Israel would continue easing the
sanctions if its demand was met.
</P>
<P>
Israel's move also came following a series of high-level
meetings between the two sides on discussing ways to resume full
cooperation in combating terrorism and rebuild the lost
confidence.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday night, Netanyahu's attorney Yitzhak Molcho met
secretly with PNA leader Yasser Arafat in Gaza to express thank to
him for the Palestinian police's quick action in arresting the
three murderers in Jericho. Arafat reportedly demanded Israel
lift the closure and transfer the tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli and Palestinian security heads held a new
round of meeting in the Palestinian city Ramallah to discuss
future security cooperation and the Israeli sanctions. The
meeting was attended by officials from the United States Central
Intelligence Agency station in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The tripartite security meeting was a result of the four-day
shuttle mission here early last week by U.S. peace envoy Dennis
Ross.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Israeli security officials asked to examine
the explosives found in a bomb factory in Beit Sahur, near
Jerusalem, which was run by the militant Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas), who claimed responsibility for the Jerusalem
bombings.
</P>
<P>
Israel's easing of the sanctions will further pave the way for
a pending visit to the region by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, who conditions her first Middle East tour on progress in
Israeli-Palestinian security cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
