<HEADLINE> IFP Leader Demands Returning Documents Taken by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Inkatha Freedom Party
(IFP) leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi has vowed to force Walter
Felgate to return documents he had taken before defecting to the
ruling African National Congress last week.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi, leader of the biggest black opposition party in
South Africa, made the remarks against the backdrop of Felgate's
disclosure that he was writing a book on politics, dealing with
the period 1974 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
Felgate, a former right-hand man to Buthelezi and his speech
writer for years, defected to ANC on August 14, accusing Inkatha
of lacking democracy within its structure.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Felgate's defection, Buthelezi told a press
conference at the weekend that Felgate had acted illegally by
taking the documents.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi said the documents included minutes of the former
Kwazulu provincial cabinet and memorandums he had exchanged with
Felgate.
</P>
<P>
The documents had been accumulated over 17 years when Felgate
was employed by the former Kwazulu government as a research
officer, he said, adding that Felgate had signed a contract with
the government that the documents would not be published without
his authority.
</P>
<P>
However, Felgate denied Buthelezi's allegation, stressing
Buthelezi could do nothing about the fact he had the documents,
which, he said, were mainly speeches of Buthelezi and the IFP
leader had copies of them.
</P>
<P>
Felgate noted that he had also given the Kwazulu provincial
government copies of everything he had written for it.
</P>
<P>
He said the documents would provide background material for a
book on politics he had started writing, covering the period 1974
to 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
