<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Firm to Run Nigerian Refinery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- French oil firm Total has signed
with the Nigerian government a contract valued at 160 to 220
million U.S. Dollars for repairing a major Nigerian refinery and
managing it for three years.
</P>
<P>
"This Day" reported today that the contract is part of an
agreement between Total and the Nigeria National Petroleum
Corporation to revitalize Nigeria's refinery industry.
</P>
<P>
Being a major world oil producer, however, Nigeria has been
suffering constant fuel shortage in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
Of its four refineries, only the new Port Harcourt refinery
and the Warri refineries are still functioning with limited
capacities. The old Port Harcourt was destroyed by a fire in
1980s.
</P>
<P>
The Kaduna refinery and Petro-Chemical company was built in
the 1980s with a capacity of processing 110,000 barrels of crude
oil a day. It is responsible for supplying fuel to the northern
part of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The refinery, however, was shut down about a month ago due to
unit failure, as poor management and the lack of money to conduct
the periodical turn around maintenance have been forcing it to
operate on a shaky base.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government took over the responsibilities of
refining and distributing from foreign oil firms about three
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
Its past suggestions of contracting foreign firms to manage
the refineries or leasing the refineries to them have been
rejected, as foreign firms feared the enabling environment for
such deal does not exist. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
