<DOCNO> XIE19970818.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Famine Looms in S. Leone As Food Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone has topped the list
of nations where a food crisis looms, beating drought-prone
Ethiopia, Somalia and Sudan, according to the Food and
Agricultural Organization (FAO).
</P>
<P>
The food situation in Sierra Leone is deteriorating rapidly
and could develop into famine if the current widespread
insecurity persists, the Daily Times reported today, quoting an
FAO official.
</P>
<P>
The security situation started to worsen since coupists
overthrew the civilian government led by ousted President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah on May 25.
</P>
<P>
International aid workers have been evacuated and
rehabilitation projects have been put on hold, while up to 20,000
people have fled to neighboring countries, mostly Guinea and
Gambia, said Mwita Rukandema of United Nations organization.
</P>
<P>
According to FAO, "the food supply situation is tightening in
the main towns. The price of rice has tripled in the capital
Freetown and the supply of food and water is deteriorating. An
acute food shortage is also reported and severely affects all
economic activities."
</P>
<P>
Only one-fifth of the shops and markets have reopened since
the May 25 coup. Limited food distribution to vulnerable people
in Freetown, Bo in the south, Kenema in the southeast and Makeni
in the North are underway for about 26,000 people, a FAO report
said.
</P>
<P>
This worsening food supply situation, according to observers,
is expected to be intensified with the reinforcement of sanctions
and blockade by west African countries in a bid to force the
coupists to step down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
