<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Medical Heritage Gets Donation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Museum of
Medical Science, a facility dedicated to the medical history of
the city, received a one-million-HK-dollar (128,000 US dollars)
donation, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
The presentation of the check was witnessed Sunday by some 50
youngsters who visited the Edwardian-style building in Mid-Levels.
</P>
<P>
The visit was part of a series of heritage-related activities
organized by the Home Affairs Department in support of the current
Heritage Year and the Summer Youth Program.
</P>
<P>
The museum's Chairman Dr. Gerald Choa said the museum was the
first such facility dedicated to exploring the interface between
traditional Chinese and Western medicine.
</P>
<P>
The building, which used to be occupied by the old Pathological
Institute, served both as an educational venue and a secure
location for the preservation of medical artifacts of historical
value, Choa said.
</P>
<P>
The new donation, contributed by the Lord Wilson Heritage
Trust, the Hang Seng Bank and several philanthropists, will help
maintain exhibition rooms, a lecture hall and other facilities of
the museum.  
</P>
