<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Dies in Nigerian Community Conflicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- No fewer than 10 persons were
feared dead and about 100 injured in violent clashes between two
communities in southwest Nigeria's Osun state at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Local media said the event began with a peaceful demonstration
on Friday by about 5,000 Modakeke youths, in protest of
relocating the Ife-east local government headquarters from
Modakeke to Oke-Ogbo in Ile-Ife.
</P>
<P>
The denouncement of the Ife leader by Modakeke youths
reportedly caused anger of the Ife people. When more students
joined both sides on Saturday, the fighting escalated from
throwing stones at each other to exchanging gunfires and burning
down houses.
</P>
<P>
The clashes continued from Saturday night into Sunday morning.
Dane guns, matchets, axes and broken bottles were used by both
sides. About 25 houses and many vehicles and other properties
were sprayed with inflammable materials and set on fire.
</P>
<P>
The clashes reportedly paralyzed all motor movement in and out
of the state and kept all residents in the area in their houses.
</P>
<P>
As at mid-Sunday, anti-riot police have been deployed to the
area and the situation has begun to calm down, while the state
government has announced a curfew from 6:00 p.m. to 7:00 a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
