<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Plans to Participate in New Commonwealth Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is considering
participating in a 200 million US dollars fund to be launched by
the Commonwealth to provide assistance to South Asian nations like
India and Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The request for Malaysia's participation was made by
Commonwealth Secretary-General Chief Emeka Anyaoku when he met
Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim here
today, Malaysian Finance Secretary Hadenan Abdul Jalil said.
</P>
<P>
Hadenan told reporters after the hour-long meeting that
Malaysia's Employees Provident Fund (EPF) might contribute to the
fund.
</P>
<P>
The EPF had previously contributed 10 million US dollars to
another Commonwealth Fund set up to provide assistance to African
nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official said so far the Commonwealth itself had pledged to
contribute 50 million US dollars to the South Asia fund through
the Commonwealth Development Corporation, while Singapore and
India have agreed to provide 30 million US dollars each.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia's decision on whether to contribute to the
fund through the EPF would depend on the returns and viability.
</P>
<P>
Hadenan said that at today's meeting, Anyaoku also requested
Malaysia to consider contributing to several Commonwealth
initiatives such as the Center of Islamic Studies in Oxford and a
rain forest research project in Guyana.
</P>
<P>
He said Anyaoku also briefed Anwar on next month's Commonwealth
Finance Ministers meeting in Mauritius where Anwar is expected to
attend and speak on the regional economy.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku is on a five-day visit here as part of a tour of
Commonwealth nations to brief leaders of member countries on the
preparation for the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting
(CHOGM) in Edinburgh in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
