<HEADLINE> Mongolian Opposition Leader Wins Parliament Seat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The leader of Mongolia's
opposition party, Nambaryn Enkhayar, was elected into the Great
Hural, or parliament, preliminary results showed today.
</P>
<P>
Enkhbayar, chairman of the Mongolian People's Revolutionary
Party (MPRP), won 72 percent of the vote in Sunday's by-election
in the country's western Zavkhan province, to fill the seat left
vacant after Natsagyn Bagabandy was elected state president in May.
</P>
<P>
The election ensures the MPRP to hold one third of the 76 seats
in the Great Hural and is helpful in keeping the balance in the
parliament, a MPRP spokesman told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Enkhbayar, 39, once served as general secretary of the party
and a member of the Great Hural. He was the cultural minister
before his party lost the general elections last year.
</P>
<P>
In the by-election, four candidates contested for the only
seat, including a candidate from the ruling Democratic Union
Coalition who pocketed 19.8 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition holds 50 seats in the parliament, the MPRP
25 and the Traditional United Party one. 
</P>
</TEXT>
