<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Dispels Notion of Overheating Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime minister
Mahathir Mohamed said today his country has to be developed faster
to give the people every chance to enjoy a higher standard of
living and to catch up with developed nations.
</P>
<P>
Brushing aside foreign criticism that the country was
developing too fast and that the economy was overheating, Mahathir
said Malaysia was left behind during the colonial period.
</P>
<P>
"We have to move fast and run faster. If we were to run slower,
we will never catch up and the gap would be even greater and
forever, we will be left behind," he was quoted by the Malaysian
national news agency Bernama as saying when officiating at the
ground breaking for the Miri City Fan and Cultural Center in
Sarawak, East Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"It is not over-heating, it is well-planned development," he
said, adding development projects were being carried out
throughout the nation with tower cranes easily seen everywhere
including in Sabah and Sarawak.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said his government was not interested in building
monuments but in development that could improve the living
standards of the people.
</P>
<P>
"We are prepared to work hard to enrich the country for the
better life of the people," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The West have good cities developed over hundreds of years but
when we are doing that, they said we are developing too fast, too
ambitious, living beyond our capacity and no money to provide fund
for this. Why do these people criticize us when we only want to
give our people a good life?" he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Sarawak state had underwent tremendous
development over the last 15 years, more people now owned cars and
all major towns are connected by roads.  
</P>
</TEXT>
