<DOCNO> XIE19970818.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen To Obtain Water From Dongjiang River Reservoir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Completion of a Dongjiang
River reservoir will relieve water shortages in Shenzhen,
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
An expert panel from the Ministry of Water Resources and the
Chinese Academy of Sciences recently approved a plan for a water
diversion pipeline linking the Xinfengjiang Reservoir with
Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
The south China city has suffered from a severe water shortage
resulting from rapid economic and social development in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
The city recorded a 30 percent increase in total demand for
water during the first six months, with the water demand in Hong
Kong growing by 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
A research report released by the Social Economic Research
Center under the Guangdong Provincial Government predicts that
Shenzhen's demand for water, both private and industrial, will hit
1.4 billion cu.m. daily by the year 2000. The actual water supply
capacity of 970 million cu.m. will fall 430 million cu.m. short of
demand.
</P>
<P>
In July of 1996, the Water Resources Bureau of Guangdong
Province approved Shenzhen's plan to divert 350 million cu.m. of
water annually from the Dongjiang River Valley which flows north
of the city.
</P>
<P>
Heyuan City introduced a proposal indicating that the most
efficient method for supply water to the city would be to
construct a pipeline linking it to the Xinfengjiang Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
Several water resources institutes, and institutes for
prospecting, survey and design from the ministries of water
resources and power industry have been invited to inspect into the
actual sites and produce feasibility studies.
</P>
<P>
Experts on the appraisal panel say that the water diversion
pipeline will offer an effective way to provide eastern areas of
Shenzhen with high quality water and to alleviate shortages of
water resources facing the city by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
They estimate the annual water diversion volume of 350 million
cu.m. from Xinfengjiang Reservoir will only account for 5.7
percent of the reservoir's total water storage volume and will
have little impact on the facility's ability to combat flooding
and to generate power. The also say the project will have no
impact on the water supply, navigation, irrigation and environment
in the lower reaches of the Dongjiang River. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
