<HEADLINE> 200 Pilots, Engineers Leave Iran for Better Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Some 200 pilots and flight
engineers have left Iran for better jobs and higher pay since the
1979 Islamic revolution due to grim economic prospects at home,
the Persian daily Salam reported today.
</P>
<P>
It said that in the past year alone, some 50 pilots and flight
engineers have emigrated to such countries as Malaysia, South
Korea, Japan and Luxembourg where they have found higher-pay
jobs.
</P>
<P>
"The highest pay rate for an Iranian pilot is 1.5 million
rials (500 U.S. dollars) per month whereas the same pilot would
receive 5,000 dollars in Malaysia," an Iranian pilot told the
daily.
</P>
<P>
Another pilot complained about the obsolescence of the planes
used in Iran, which he said worries Iranian pilots.
</P>
<P>
"In addition to receiving low wages, Iranian pilots have to
fly old planes whereas in other countries such as Malaysia, they
fly new planes which are safer," he added.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted another pilot as saying that he objected to
the body search of the Iranian pilots at the Iranian airports.
</P>
<P>
He said that before boarding the plane, the pilots have to go
through body search which is insulting for the pilots.
</P>
</TEXT>
