<HEADLINE> Hainan Economy Grows 7.2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Hainan, an island province in
south China, registered a gross domestic product of 17.9 billion
yuan in the first half of this year, up 7.2 percent from the 1996
period.
</P>
<P>
The province registered an overall increase in output for
grain, sugar, fruit and vegetables in the first half of the year,
with grain production reaching 1.15 million tons and vegetable
output hitting 1.64 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The industrial sector ended the period with 2.25 billion yuan
in added value, up 15.4 percent from the corresponding 1996
period. In addition, the province's investments in fixed assets
have grown by over 40 percent annually in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Hainan hosted over 2.43 million tourists during the period, a
rise of 18.2 percent and a record high for the past eight
years. Foreign exchange earnings from tourism reached 50.76
million US dollars, representing 27.8 percent growth on the
previous year's period.
</P>
<P>
The economic resurgence followed two years of steady economic
growth. Hainan's 1996 GDP of 39.8 billion yuan represented a
six-fold jump on 1987. In 1988, Hainan became a province.
</P>
<P>
Hainan's service sector attracted the lion's share of
investments and witnessed rapid development between 1991-1992,
while the industrial and agricultural sectors continued to lag
behind.
</P>
<P>
The new round of economic reform introduced in 1993 has helped
the province restructure its development infrastructure and follow
a healthy track of economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
