<HEADLINE> Ramos Orders to Ensure Safety of Life at Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today lamented the loss of lives in the two sea tragedies that hit
the country within 24 hours last Friday, leaving at least 19
people dead and a number of others missing.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony held here to mark the 2nd National
Seafarers' Day, Ramos ordered the entire marine industry and the
departments of transportation and communications and national
defense to take joint efforts to ensure the safety of life at sea.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the two sea mishaps underlined the need "to stop,
prevent and punish the neglect and greed that lead to the
unnecessary loss of lives, property and goodwill arising out of
such maritime calamities."
</P>
<P>
Also today, a police officer from Manila's Western Police
District Homicide Division told Xinhua that homicide charges have
been filed against the owner, the captain and two operators of the
tourist boat which capsized late last Friday in Manila Bay.
</P>
<P>
The sightseeing boat overturned off the bay and just in front
of the Philippine Navy Headquarters reportedly because of strong
winds and high waves, killing seven Hong Kong tourists.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary investigation showed that the boat, with a
permitted capacity of only about 23 people, was badly overloaded.
The small wooden boat sank with a total of 49 people on board.
</P>
<P>
In another sea tragedy, an inter-island passenger ship carrying
137 people sank before dawn last Friday in Biliran province in the
central Philippines, initially killing 12 people. As of this
morning, a Coast Guard officer said, none of the 16 missing
passengers were spotted.
</P>
<P>
Transportation and Communications Secretary Arnuto Enrile said
Sunday he would convene a maritime consultative conference among
all government agencies, including the police and military, to
draw up a comprehensive action plan designed to prevent maritime
accidents.
</P>
<P>
Ramos earlier ordered Enrile to undertake a thorough
investigation into the two sea tragedies and punish those
violators of the country's safety of life at sea law.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
