<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 08:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Economic Growth Down to 1.6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli economy grew by
an annual 1.6 percent in the second quarter this year, according
to a report published today by the Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
During the January-July period, the economy grew by an annual
2 percent, thus continuing a clear slowdown trend which began in
late 1995, when semi-annual growth was still at 6 percent, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs said that
the number of job seekers in July rose by 1.1 percent to
145,600. Over 55 percent of July's job-seekers were newly
unemployed, a roughly 12 percent increase since the beginning of
the year. In all, 16,815 new job seekers have been registered
this year.
</P>
<P>
However, some of that rise was attributable to the steady
arrival of new immigrants, most of them are initially
jobless. Even so, current unemployment level, 7.7 percent of the
work force, is a three-year high.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the number of joblessness is rapidly
expanding in the periphery's development towns. The number of
cities with 10 percent or higher unemployment rates rose last
month to 17, compared with eight in April.
</P>
<P>
Though the discouraging data might give reason to contemplate
an easing of the Bank of Israel's monetary policy, an
interest-rate cut now seems less likely, considering the central
bank's report released Sunday that money supply rose 5.4 percent
last month.
</P>
<P>
The increase in money supply was attributed primarily to the
relatively sharp, 1.2 percent interest-rate cut which came in
tandem with the expansion of the shekel's fluctuation bands in
June.
</P>
<P>
In all, money supply has risen by 13 percent so far this
year. Set against this backdrop, it is unlikely that central bank
governor Jacob Frenkel will cut interest rates for September, and
in fact he may decide to raise them in order to help the
government meet its own annual inflation target of 7 to 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
The slow-down in Israel's economic growth is largely due to
the Likud government's belt-tightening policy aimed at cutting
the inflation and budgetary deficit.
</P>
<P>
Since coming to power in June last year, the government has
cut 8 billion shekels (2.3 billion U.S. dollars) from the 1997
budget, and the annual economic growth in 1997 slowed down
consequently to about 4 percent, compared with an average of 6
percent in the past years.
</P>
<P>
On August 13, the cabinet approved the 1998 budget by cutting
2.3 billion shekels (657 million dollars) in public expenditures
and setting 1998's annual target rate of inflation at 7 to 10
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970818.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
