<HEADLINE> Middlemen Found to Be High Newsprint Cost Root in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The proliferation of middlemen
and lack of a reliable pulp and paper mill are responsible for the
high cost of newsprint in Zambia, a printing managing director
has said.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted John Mpundu, managing director of
job printing agencies as saying Sunday in northern Zambia that
prices of imported newsprint will continue to rise unless local
sources are found.
</P>
<P>
He complained that there are too many middlemen dealing
newsprint and other printing accessories resulting in high
prices.
</P>
<P>
Big printing firms such as those owned by leading local
newspaper companies are making little or no profit because much
of the money is spent on procuring newsprint, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Unless Zambia sets up its pulp and paper mill plant, middlemen
will continue to make a rip off," Mpundu warned.
</P>
<P>
The middlemen are charging twice as much as the normal cost of
imported newsprint.
</P>
<P>
Reasonable prices for a ton of newsprint are pegged at between
800 U.S. Dollars and 1,000 Dollars, but the middlemen sell a ton
at the price of more than 1,500 Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
