<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Fight Hyacinth With Beetles in L. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is to fight the
over-fast-growing water hyacinth on Lake Victoria with beetles in
a 20.4 million U.S. Dollars environmental conservation program.
</P>
<P>
The project has been made public at the on-going national
assembly session, according to the vice-president's office.
</P>
<P>
About 10.1 million Dollars of the sum will be donated by the
World Bank. The Global Environmental Facility, a special fund
also administered by the world bank, is expected to chip in some
10.3 million Dollars, with the government contributing the rest
of the funds, Bakari Mbonde, the minister of state in the
vice-president's office said.
</P>
<P>
Mbonde said, "in the 1997/98 financial year, the funds will
cater for increased patrol in the lake zone to demarcate areas
for fishing, research on environmental pollution and better use
of wetland."
</P>
<P>
The environmental conservation unit in the vice-president's
office has entered into a coordinated program with Kenya and
Uganda on the lake environment.
</P>
<P>
Biological control measures like introducing swarms of beetles
to eat up the weeks are in progress with breeding being conducted
at Kibaha.
</P>
<P>
An initial quantity of inbred beetles will soon be sent to
Mwanza. Meanwhile, a similar project is being coordinated on the
Lake Tanganyika basin.
</P>
<P>
Burundi, Zambia and the Democratic Republic of Congo are
collaborating in the project, according to Mbonde. 
</P>
</TEXT>
