<HEADLINE> Fujian Reports Growth in Aquatic Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, August 18 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province
netted in 1.36 million ton of aquatics products in the first half
of this year, up 18.3 percent from the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Total output figures included 732,000 tons of marine products,
and 174,000 tons of artificially-bred products.
</P>
<P>
Six coastal prefectures and cities have transformed 1,000 ha of
shallows into aquatic breeding zones in recent year, with the kelp
output growing by 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Breeding bases of precious aquatic products, including prawns,
abalone, eels and soft-shelled turtles, have been expanded. The
city of Zhangzhou alone built 56 new abalone breeding farms and
sold 23 tons of abalone during the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The province has recorded notable progress in introducing new
technology needed for artificial breeding, and currently leads the
world in breeding large yellow croakers. 
</P>
