<HEADLINE> Philippines' Electronics Exports Seen to Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' exports of
electronics, its top foreign reserve earner, are expected to reach
14 billion U.S. dollars this year, increasing 32 percent over last
year, the Philippine News Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
Pushed by robust exports of electronics and components, the
country's exports will reach 20 billion dollars as projected by
the year 2000, the agency said, quoting a recent report from the
Trade and Industry Department.
</P>
<P>
The continued robust exports will enable the Philippines to
maintain a relatively stable foreign exchange rate in the next 10
years, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
For the first five months of this year, exports of electronics
hit 5.6 billion dollars, reflecting a hefty 41.89 percent increase
over the 3.9 billion dollars in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Top export markets for the country's electronic products
include the United States, Japan, Singapore and Thailand.
</P>
</TEXT>
