<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 08:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Military Plays Down Turkey-Iran Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish military has
expressed pessimism over a positive change in the souring
Turkey-Iran relations despite the election of a moderate president
in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News today quoted senior military
sources, who declined to be named, as saying that President
Mohammad Khatami's coming to power must not bring about a warmer
era between Ankara and Tehran.
</P>
<P>
Recognizing Khatami, who took office August 4, as a moderate
politician, the sources said he would meet challenges from Islamic
hardliners although he intended to conduct liberal reform in a
country ruled by Shariah, or Islamic law.
</P>
<P>
"It is certain that he will face severe difficulties, which
will also affect Turkey, from the country's dominant religious
structure headed by the powerful spiritual leader Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei," the sources said.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that despite Khatami himself's moderate
tendency, Iran's internal and external policies would be finally
determined by the powerful religious structure instead of the
government.
</P>
<P>
Under Iran's current political system, the president is
subordinate to the spiritual leader, who appeared reluctant to to
show his support for Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, who advocates more rights and freedom for women, is
considered as a hopeful figure to relatively bridge the deep gap
between the Islamic state and the Western world, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The spiritual leader, however, has the final say on Iran's
political, military and social policies, which is believed to be a
key block to the new president's future reforms, they added.
</P>
<P>
The Military sources voiced that Turkish-Iranian relations
could not be improved unless Tehran made a significant change in
its policy toward the secular Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian government has not given up its traditional cards
against Turkey, such as backing the outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK) rebels and encouraging fundamentalist movement in
Turkey, the sources claimed.
</P>
<P>
In February, Turkey expelled several Iranian diplomats,
including its ambassador to Ankara, because of their "improper
speeches made at a religious rally held by Turkey's extremist
Islamists," touching off a war of words between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military, which is firmly opposed to the previous
pro-Islamic government's efforts to develop closer ties with
Tehran, always voiced their concern over alleged Iran's attempt to
intervene in Turkey's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish military's increasingly frequent cooperation
with the Israeli army and its cross-border campaign against the
PKK in northern Iraq have come under sharp criticism from
Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
