<HEADLINE> hke081819--Philippine Central Bank to Stay Out of Currency Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines will continue to stay away from the foreign exchange
market this week and traders expect the peso will further
depreciate to between 30 to 31 pesos against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports today quoted Central Bank Managing Director
Amando Tetangco as saying that the combined effects of strong
demand for dollars from importers and the pressure exerted by
declining Southern Asian currencies are pushing the peso down.
</P>
<P>
He said that the central bank has decided to stop propping up
the currency, which depreciated to around 29.76 pesos to the
dollar last week.
</P>
<P>
"Why would you intervene? We will let the market determine the
level of the exchange rate," he said, ruling out the possibility
of increasing the bank's overnight rates to arrest the
depreciation of the peso.
</P>
<P>
Traders here said that the market will test the 30 pesos-one
dollar level this week.
</P>
<P>
The central bank will likely keep its overnight rates at 14
percent since it does not want to choke off economic growth with
high interest rates, they said.
</P>
<P>
The bank raised its overnight borrowing rate to 32 percent last
month to combat speculations, but slashed it gradually to 14
percent by last week.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that if the central bank keeps interest rates
high, there is going to be a recession.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970818.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State-Owned Assets Grow 15.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The value of China's state-owned
assets reached 6,589 billion yuan (794 billion US dollars) at the
end of 1996, up 15.4 percent from the previous year's figure.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown of state assets statistics released during
a national meeting indicates that productive assests of more
than 4,993 billion yuan accounted for 75.8 percent of the total,
and non-productive assets of 1,595 billion yuan accounted for
the remaining 24.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Basic sectors -- posts and telecommunications, power
generation, railway transportation and petroleum -- accounted for
28.1 percent of total assest for state-owned enterprises, up 24.8
percent on 1995.
</P>
<P>
Large and medium-sized state-owned enterprises, which account
for 19.9 percent of all state-owned enterprises, had a combined
asset value of over 8,923 billion yuan, or 75 percent of the
total. Part of the assets of state-owned enterprises is owned by
the non-state sector, including Sino-foreign joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
The aggregate asset volume of small state-owned enterprises,
which account for 80.1 percent of all state-owned enterprises,
stood at 25 percent of the total.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
