<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Senator Witnesses Remarkable Changes in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Mexican senator Gustavo Caravajal
Moreno said that he has witnessed a happy population in Tibet,
which is keeping pace with the modern times.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark after recently completing a tour of the
Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Senator Moreno, who also serves as vice-president of the
Inter-Parliamentary Union, visited Tibet between Aug. 8-12. He
arrived in the region from Japan and was bound for various African
countries to discuss candidates for the next president of the
union.
</P>
<P>
Moreno noted the great changes which have taken place since his
first visit to Tibet's capital of Lhasa in 1973. He particularly
noted the broad streets, bustling business, modern facilities and
luxury hotels along the highway from the Gonggar Airport to
Lhasa. Moreno pointed to the totally different environment
compared to his visit 24 years ago, and noted that Tibet has bid
farewell to serfdom and entered modern society.
</P>
<P>
The senator learned that some 300,000 students attend Tibet's
over 4,000 schools, and that more than 10,000 Tibetan students are
studying in Tibetan schools or related classes in over 20
provinces and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
He also learned that the central government has invested more
than 40 billion yuan (4.8 billion US dollars) in improving the
region's infrastructure, with some 3.6 billion yuan spent in 62
infrastructure projects over the past four years alone.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Tibet's economy has grown by over ten percent
annually in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Moreno said the Chinese government has done its utmost to
ensure the rights of Tibetan people, including the right to an
education.
</P>
<P>
The senator was deeply impressed by the preferential policies
the central government provides for Tibet. For example, Tibetan
farmers, herdsmen and township enterprises are exempt from income
tax, and the central government subsidizes the budgets of local
governments.
</P>
<P>
Moreno said he has never believed distorted reports and unjust
comments made by some media organizations in the West.
</P>
<P>
"They are totally unaware of how Tibetan people live," said
Moreno.
</P>
<P>
The senator said the happy smiles on the faces of Tibetans
served as a true indication of their happy lives. He also
reiterated his belief that the Chinese government will continue to
help Tibet achieve faster and sounder development.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the regional autonomy of Tibet and the relationship
between the local and central governments, he stressed that the
international community must acknowledge the fact that most
Tibetan people support unification.
</P>
<P>
Moreno also noted that had the opportunity to a Tibetan dinner
prepared by the former chef for the late 10th Panchen Lama.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
