<HEADLINE> Triad Security Talks Begin in West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
security officials met last night under the eye of
U.S. officials to discuss security cooperation between the two
sides, the state-run Israeli Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting in the West Bank town of Ramallah was held within a
trangular framework laid down by U.S. special envoy Dennis Ross
during his four-day mediation mission here last week.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Israeli officials expressed interest in
examining the explosives found in a bomb factory of the Islamic
militant group Hamas which was raided by Palestinian police
recently.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side asked Israel to drop the series of
measures it has taken strangling Palestinian economic life after
the Jerusalem market bombing on July 30, which killed 16 people
and wounded 170 more.
</P>
<P>
The Israelis said during the meeting that they were satisfied
with the cooperation of Palestinian security forces in the
investigation of the market bombing. Both sides agreed to meet
again later this week.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Cabinet secretary Danny Navey said after the meeting
that the economic sanctions imposed on Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) since the market bombing may be eased following
increased security cooperation between Israel and Palestine.
</P>
<P>
He said Palestinian security officials have provided Israel
with results of the lab tests carried out on explosives founded in
the Hamas bomb factory.
</P>
<P>
But he added that releasing funds to Palestine does not mean
Israel is convenced that PNA Chairmen Yasser Arafat is doing all
he can to dismantle terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
Israel has been withholding, since the suicide bombings, some
70 million U.S. dollars in tax and customs revenues it collected
from Palestinians and due the PNA in accordance with their
agreements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
