<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Eats Into Arab Budgets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Arabs spend up to half their
income on food while most of their needs for farming products are
met from abroad because of poor domestic production, an Arab food
official said.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview in the latest edition of the business
weekly Al Iqtesadi, Falah Jabr, head of the Arab Food Industries
Union, said Arab citizens allocate between 25 and 50 percent of
their income to foodstuffs each year.
</P>
<P>
"Arab food imports are estimated at 35 billion dollars a
year. We are importing nearly 10 percent of the world's total
food trade," Jabr said.
</P>
<P>
Arabs also import nearly 20 percent of the world's wheat
supplies, 15 percent of the cereals, and 60 percent of the
livestock, he added.
</P>
<P>
Jabr estimated total investment by the 22-member Arab League
in the farming sector at around 50 billion dollars a year, but
said production was growing by only 2 percent a year while
consumption was rising by 6-7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
