<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Modern Use of Fans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The fan, an indispensable article
to drive away summer heat by Chinese people for centuries, seems
to have been vanished as electric fans and air conditioners
have entered into more Chinese families.
</P>
<P>
But this year, fans have become easy-to-sell goods in Hangzhou,
capital city of east China's Zhejiang province, after years of
seclusion.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that over 1,0000 fans, made of paper,
silk, bamboo, straw and feather, were sold per day in some of the
city's famous fan shops like Tiangong Yiyuan and Wang Xingji
during the last two months.
</P>
<P>
The Fan Festival organized by some fan shops always attract a
great number of people. To promote sales, some shops have even
invited renowned writers to inscribe poems on fans for customers.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that 99 percent of households in Hangzhou,
known as an "oven" in China, have bought electric fans or air
conditioners. Then why has there been a fan-purchase craze?
</P>
<P>
"With the living standards improved, people try to make their
life colorful. It has become a fashion nowadays to use fans as a
decoration or gists to friends and relatives," said a manager of
Wang Xingji Factory, the oldest fan manufacturer in China.
</P>
<P>
Sometimes, hundreds of people come to buy fans for wall
decoration in a single day. We have to adapt our production for
the varied needs," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 100-year old factory, which used to focus on producing
black paper folding fans, has developed over 400 kinds of fans
this year to meet customers' different needs. There is a rich
variety in the materials of the fans' covering, including paper,
feather, silk, bamboo, grass, bone and leaf, making fans more
appealing to fan lovers.
</P>
<P>
A young couple, who had bought a two-meter-wide silk fan from
the Tiangong Yiyuan Shop, said they would use the fan to decorate
the parlor of their new apartment.
</P>
<P>
"It's quite elegant and distinctive to use a fan as
decoration," the husband said.
</P>
<P>
Fans have been used in people's daily life more widely than
ever before. In the morning, senior people played Yangko (a folk
dance) on the bank of the West Lake, the best-known scenic spot in
Hangzhou, with silk fans in their hands, forming a unique
scenery. Young ladies with pocket sandalwood fans look more
graceful.
</P>
<P>
At present, an ordinary paper fan with painting or poems from
famous painters or calligraphers can be a gift of fine taste to a
friend or a business partner, and the exquisitely made precious
sandalwood fans are rated as popular goods for collectors these
days.
</P>
<P>
The earlist fan makers might never imagine that one day fans
would be treasured in the elegant boxes or put up high on the
wall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970818.0122 </DOCNO>
