<HEADLINE> Cultural Exchanges across Taiwan Straits Increasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Some 1,036 artists from Chinese
inland areas and Taiwan, or 107 more artists than in 1996,
participated in 108 cultural exchanges during the first half of
this year.
</P>
<P>
According to a Ministry of Culture official, "The two sides
abide by the principles of mutual respect, sincerity, practicality
and people-to-people relations when developing cultural exchanges."
</P>
<P>
The inland areas offer Taiwan outstanding cultural programs
featuring Chinese traditional culture and national characteristics.
</P>
<P>
A lantern display from north China's Shanxi Province and the
Quanzhou Puppet Show Troupe from Fujian Province attracted more
than two million people during a tour of Taiwan over this year's
traditional Chinese Lunar New Year Festival.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a combined group of performers, including members
of the Tianjin-Beijing Opera Troupe, attracted large audiences
for 10 performances in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Beijing opera training courses have been offered in Taiwan for
the past four years, with 74 teachers from schools in inland areas
teaching students excerpts from 100 traditional operas.
</P>
<P>
Some 307 Taiwanese artists visited inland areas during the
period, a dramatic 73 percent increase from the 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the number of visitors to inland areas
on cultural exchanges will continue to grow in the second half of
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
