<HEADLINE> Top Queen's Counsels in Singapore for "Historic Legal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Two Queen's Counsels with what
is said "formidable reputations" are in action in a 12-day court
case starting here today between 11 ruling People's Action Party
(PAP) leaders and opposition Workers' Party chief J.B. Jeyaretnam,
the Straits Times reported.
</P>
<P>
It said Thomas Shields, Queen's Counsel, will open the case in
the High Court with a submission on behalf of his client, Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong, who will take the stand after the opening
act in a case which has attracted international attention.
</P>
<P>
At least two observers from international human rights groups,
the Amnesty International and the International Commission of
Jurists, are here to monitor the hearing, described by the Times
of London newspaper as a "historic legal confrontation", the
Straits Times said.
</P>
<P>
After taking questions from Shields, Prime Minister Goh will be
cross-examined by George Carman, the Queen's Counsel hired by
Jeyaretnam to fight eight defamation suits.
</P>
<P>
The PAP leaders, including Prime Minister Goh and Senior
Minister Lee Kuan Yew, are suing Jeyaretnam for telling a Workers'
Party election campaign rally on January 1 this year that his
team-mate in the Cheng San Group Representation Constituency,
lawyer Tang Liang Hong, had just placed before him two reports the
latter made to the police against the Prime Minister and his team.
</P>
<P>
The PAP leaders claimed the words Jeyaretnam used implied that
they had conspired to commit criminal defamation against Tang by
labeling him an anti-Christian, anti-English educated Chinese
chauvinist.
</P>
<P>
The Times of London quoted Jeyaretnam as saying last Wednesday
that Lee was out to make him a bankrupt and force him to give up
his Non-Constituency MP seat in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Lee and other PAP leaders are also expected to take the stand
before Justice S. Rajendran over the next 12 days, the Straits
Times report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Straits Times, Shields specializes in libel
work and was involved in several important cases, while Carman is
among the top libel lawyers in London.  
</P>
</TEXT>
