<HEADLINE> Japan's Merchandise Trade Surplus Grew 69.7 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus
in July grew 69.7 percent from a year earlier to 849.1 billion yen
(7.3 billion U.S. dollars), the Finance Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the expansion to strong exports of
automobiles to Europe and the United States, and exports of office
equipments including personal computers and semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
Of the figure, exports increased 12.1 percent to 4288.5 billion
yen (36.9 billion dollars), the 24th consecutive monthly rise,
while imports advanced 3.4 percent to 3439.4 billion yen (29.7
billion dollars) for the 39th straight monthly expansion, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's politically sensitive trade surplus with the United
States rose to 420.5 billion yen (3.6 billion dollars), up 35.7
percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
In trade with the U.S., exports advanced 11.8 percent to
1,193.7 billion yen (10.3 billion dollars) while imports edged up
2.0 percent to 773.1 billion yen (6.7 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Japan also posted increases in its trade surplus with the
European Union (EU) and Asia, boosted by growing exports of
automobiles and semiconductors, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The surplus with the EU jumped 156.4 percent to 140.5 billion
yen (1.2 billion dollars) while the surplus with Asian economies
increased 23.5 percent to 581.8 billion yen (5.0 billion
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
