<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Currency Devalues Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi monetary
authorities today devalued the country's currency taka again in
less than one month by about 1.01 percent in a bid to maintain a
workable level of the foreign exchange reserve by encouraging
exports and remittances.
</P>
<P>
A central bank announcement said that Bangladesh Bank's buying
and selling rates of U.S. dollar from and to authorized dealer
banks would be 44.45 taka and 44.65 taka respectively.
</P>
<P>
This is the second devaluation during the current 1997-98
fiscal year. The last downward adjustment of the taka was made on
July 20.
</P>
<P>
The latest currency devaluation is also the ninth by the Awami
(people's) League government which took power on June 23 last
year. The total amount of depreciation is 2.80 taka during the
present government.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Bank said the refixation had been effected with a
view to maintaining the incentives for remittances from Bangladesh
nationals working abroad and also the competitiveness of exports.
</P>
<P>
According to central bank sources, the foreign exchange reserve
now stood at 1.65 billion dollars which is not so comfortable, and
the country would have to make a payment in the Asian Clearing
Union next month which would shed some 120 million dollars from
the reserve.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the foreign exchange reserve level will come down
further, making the reserve more uncomfortable.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
