<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Considers Delaying Big Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government is
considering delaying some of its major projects as part of tighter
monetary and fiscal policies designed to calm the panic in the
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
"There is a possibility that some major projects will be
delayed, especially projects that are not on the main priority
list," the local press today quoted Finance Minister Mar'ie
Muhammad as saying.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto has instructed all related institutions to
reassess major projects, the minister said on Saturday after
Soeharto's state address at the parliament to mark Indonesia's
52nd independence anniversary.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto called on both government institutions and the private
sector to consolidate and make rational projections following the
fall of the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's monetary authorities floated the rupiah last week.
The currency then plunged to as low as 2,960 rupiah against the
U.S. dollar on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The stock market has also been hit hard by the currency
turmoil. The Jakarta stock index fell sharply last week to close
at 617.71 points, the lowest level this year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that many Indonesian firms will be hard hit by
the fall of the rupiah as a large amount of their borrowings are
unhedged. They estimated that Indonesian corporations have at
least 10 percent of their total foreign debt unhedged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
