<HEADLINE> Italy Warns Citizens Against Kenyan Seaside Spots Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 17 (Xinhua) -- The Italian Foreign Ministry has
advised Italian tourists to avoid traveling to Kenyan seaside
resorts of Mombasa and Malindi where repeated incidence of
violence broke out in recent days.
</P>
<P>
"Since last Thursday we have been advising all tourist
organizations against visits to Mombasa and traveling along the
road from Mombasa to Malindi," a Foreign Ministry official said
today.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 people have been reportedly killed in five days
when gangs armed with automatic rifles attacked villages around
Mombasa. But the only incidence affecting foreign tourists was a
raid on Saturday when several of them fled a guest house torched
by gangsters.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has tightened security checks and sent in
the armed forces. Tourism is Kenya's biggest source of jobs and
hard currency, generating hundreds of millions of dollars in
profit each year.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the ministry also expressed concern about the
kidnapping of 13 Italian tourists in Yemen this summer who were
released now. 
</P>
