<HEADLINE> Bodies of Two More Climbing Victims Found in Alps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Mountain rescue teams said they
have found two more bodies of climbing victims in the northern
Alpine region, the ANSA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 people have died there in climbing accidents this
summer, ANSA reported in Bolzano, an Alpine city more than 500
kilometers north of Rome.
</P>
<P>
One of the victims was identified as Fabrizia Binelli. As an
experienced 32-year-old climber, Binelli was believed to have been
struck by lightening during a violent thunderstorm Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The alarm was raised by her climbing companion this morning,
who had spent the whole night stuck on a rock face near the
2,800-meter-high Roda di Vael peak still roped to Binelli.
</P>
<P>
The other victim was 56-year-old Vittorio Fabris, who
apparently slipped on a steep slope on Mountain Luson and fell to
death while hunting for wild mushrooms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
