<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Enterprises of Shandong's Heze Prepare for Shareholding Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- All state-owned and collective
companies in Heze City, east China's Shandong Province, will be
transformed into shareholding firms within this year.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily" today quoted Mayor Yang Yongcheng as saying that
the Heze City government decided to provide full financial support
to large firms vital to local economic growth, but leave smaller
ones to be regulated by market forces.
</P>
<P>
The "partnership shareholding" will be more popular here in
Heze, well-known for growing peony flowers in China, contrasting
standard shareholding in the wester economic concept.
</P>
<P>
The special shareholding stipulates that shares be held by
employees only. Hence, it is also known as "international
shareholding". The system, initiated in rural areas in early
1980s, is aimed at solving capital shortage in small companies.
</P>
<P>
Most of China's enterprises are small in scale. The government
believes "partnership shareholding" will increase employees' work
enthusiasm and raise more money. Therefore, The State Commission
for Economic Restructuring issued a formal guideline on August 7
to spread the practice nationwide.
</P>
<P>
According to Mayor Yang, Heze, with a population of 1.2
million, will also list one of its money-making firms on
domestic bourses this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
