<HEADLINE> Kocinski Takes Overall Lead in Superbike Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, August 17 (Xinhua) -- British rider Carl Fogarty
enjoyed victory and tasted defeat in one competition at the World
Superbike Championships on Sunday, winning his first race and then
colliding in his second to relinquish his short-lived overall lead.
</P>
<P>
The Ducati rider topped the podium after the first of two races
at the A1-Ring. He was 0.297 seconds ahead of Japan's Akiro
Yanagawa on a Kawasaki and 0.615 clear of New Zealand's Aaron
Slight on a Honda.
</P>
<P>
In the first race five riders were within a second of each
other nearing the line until Fogarty broke away and won in 38
minutes 11.804 seconds after 25 laps.
</P>
<P>
But in the second, Fogarty caused a crash with his fiercest
rival, Honda rider John Kocinski, when he tried to overtake the
American.
</P>
<P>
Kocinski had just taken the lead from Fogarty when both men
slid off-track. The Briton was forced to abandon but Kocinski was
able to remount his bike and continue.
</P>
<P>
The American recovered sensationally to finish third and regain
the overall lead in the standings with 273 points to Fogarty's 267
points and Slight's 223.
</P>
<P>
The crash between the sport's two leading men allowed Yanagawa
to become the first Japanese rider to win a superbike world
championship race outside his home country.
</P>
<P>
Yanagawa crossed the finish line 0.121 seconds ahead of Slight
and 7.264 ahead of Kocinski. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
