<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson Ended up with Fifth in British 200m Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Michael Johnson, the 200 meters
world record holder and Olympic champion, was comprehensively
beaten over the distance in an athletics meeting held at Crystal
Palace on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, running for an international select team, finished
only fifth in 20.87 as veteran Welshman Doug Turner recorded 20.73
to claim an unexpected victory.
</P>
<P>
100 meters world record holder Donovan Bailey of Canada cruised
to victory in a time of 10.13 with American Vince Henderson second
in 10.22 and British teenage sensation Dwain Chambers third in
10.31.
</P>
<P>
New world champion Marius Corbett of South Africa beat off
local favourite Steve Backley to win the javelin with a throw of
87.46. Backley, second to Corbett in Athens, took the same
position on Sunday with 87.14.
</P>
<P>
Australian world champion Cathy Freeman won the women's 400
meters in 50.61, holding off Briton Allison Curbishly with a time
of 51.04.
</P>
<P>
Iwan Thomas took the men's event in 44.69, with 1991 world
champion American Antonio Pettigrew second in 44.84 and Mark
Richardson third in 45.10.
</P>
<P>
Jonathan Edwards' poor triple jump form continued as he
finished behind fellow Briton Francis Agyepong, who won with
16.72, four centimeters ahead of the world record holder
Edwards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
