<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0000 GMT, August 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- The European Monetary Union (EMU), due to be launched
on January 1 1999, will offer huge opportunities for speculators
to make millions by attacking the single currency from the start,
according to Walter Eltis, former head of Britain's National
Economic Development Office. He said that the timetable for the
EMU has been designed in such a way that it offers speculators a
free run. (UK-EMU-Speculation)
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- Six more Kenyans were killed overnight in the port
city of Mombasa, bringing the death toll to 31 since Wednesday,
the Kenya Television Network (KTN) reported Sunday. Five people
were killed and dozens of people injured during the attacks by
more than 100 gangsters at the Shauri Yako slum area, eight
kilometers north of Mombasa. Another person was shot by police and
his body burned by angry villagers Sunday morning after local
people in the area raided a neighboring slum area, accusing the
people there of attacking them. (Kenya-Port City Violence)
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel Sunday signed a
controversial education reform bill into law, marking the initial
victory of the secularists. Demirel wasted no time in signing the
eight-year compulsory education bill which was adopted by the
Parliament by a margin of 35 votes Saturday, according to the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the president made the move to show
his firm support for the Mesut Yilmaz's government, which proposed
the education reform scheme, and other secularists. (Turkey-New
Law)
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The Syrian Minister of State for Foreign Affairs
Nasser Qaddour reiterated Sunday that Syria is prepared to resume
negotiations with Israel from the very point they were suspended.
</P>
<P>
Addressing participants in the political leadership training
seminars of the Feminist Union and the Revolution Youths Union, he
said that Syria is struggling for the achievement of just and
comprehensive based on international legitimacy resolutions and
the land-for-peace principle. (Syria-Israel-Talks)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Yitzhak Molcho, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu's attorney, met secretly with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat overnight to commend Palestinian cooperation in
apprehending the murderers of an Israeli taxi driver, Israel Radio
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Molcho and Arafat was held in Gaza
Saturday night following the Palestinian court in Jericho
sentenced three Palestinians earlier in the day for murdering
Israeli cab driver Shmuel Ben Baruch Friday.
(Israel-Palestine-Secret Meeting)
</P>
<P>
SARAJEVO -- Troops of the NATO-led Stabilization Force (SFOR)
on Sunday were deployed around the headquarters of the public
security center in Banja Luka to prevent possible clashes between
police factions in the Serb territory.
</P>
<P>
A short statement by SFOR said the move was required by the
Office of the High Representative, the highest international
civilian authority in Bosnia, after the police headquarters were
taken over earlier in the day by special police loyal to Republika
Srpska President Biljana Plavsic. (Bosnia-SFOR-Acts) 
</P>
</TEXT>
