<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residents Eager for Drug Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Facing an ever-increasing threat
from narcotics, most Beijingers urge the government to strengthen
education on drug-prevention.
</P>
<P>
Over half the capital city's residents are concerned about
media reporting of anti-drug efforts, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
These are just two of the results of a sample survey on
drug-related issues which was revealed yesterday by the National
Narcotics-Control Committee, China's highest anti-drug authority.
</P>
<P>
Other questions put to respondents included: Are they aware of
drug use? Who are the major drug-users? How do they become
drug-addicts? Who is concerned about drug addicts? How serious and
harmful has the drug problem become in Beijing? The public's
comments were also invited on the government's efforts against
drugs.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted using a sample of 1,200 families with
members aged between 12 and 60 in Beijing's eight urban
districts.
</P>
<P>
Over 90 percent of those surveyed agreed that drugs will be
a major menace to morality and the Chinese nation if effective
measures are not taken against them.
</P>
<P>
Respondents hoped that heavy punishments would be given to
those involved in drug-related crimes and that government efforts
against drugs would be further intensified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
