<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doohan Wins Fourth Successive World Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 17 (Xinhua) -- Mick Doohan claimed his fourth
successive 500cc world championship title when he won the British
Grand Prix in Donington, England on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a two-bike duel with his Honda teammate Tedayuki Okada, the
32-year-old Australian, who only needed to finish in the top seven
to assure himself of the world championship, was determined to win.
</P>
<P>
Doohan, who has been riding bikes since the age of 10 and who
walks with a limp after a race fall in 1992, took the chequered
flag with 0.231 seconds to spare ahead of the dogged Okada.
</P>
<P>
The win gave Doohan his third consecutive British Grand Prix
and put him alongside Mike Hailwood and Giacomo Agostini as the
only riders in 500cc history to win four straight world titles.
</P>
<P>
Another record the man from Brisbane is hoping to achieve is
the number of race wins in one season.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Alex Barros finished third after winning a gripping
battle with Italian Luca Cadalora. 
</P>
</TEXT>
